WEBVTT

00:06.131 --> 00:09.092
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:09.092 --> 00:15.515
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.515 --> 00:18.435
<i>‐ My name's Joe Vachon</i>
<i>from Goldendale, Washington.</i>

00:18.435 --> 00:20.312
<i>What I love</i>
<i>about bladesmithing</i>

00:20.312 --> 00:22.231
is just the connection
to the elements,

00:22.231 --> 00:24.650
<i>connecting to iron and fire</i>

00:24.650 --> 00:27.110
<i>and the smells,</i>
<i>sounds, the heat.</i>

00:27.110 --> 00:30.364
It's a very amazing
experience for me.

00:30.364 --> 00:32.199
<i>‐ My name is Benton Frisse,</i>
<i>and I am 28 years old.</i>

00:32.199 --> 00:33.742
<i>I work in e‐commerce.</i>

00:33.742 --> 00:36.119
I sit behind a computer
for 40 to 50 hours.

00:36.119 --> 00:37.704
<i>Crunching numbers</i>
<i>doesn't give you</i>

00:37.704 --> 00:39.456
<i>a whole lot of ability</i>
<i>to get creative,</i>

00:39.456 --> 00:41.750
<i>so it's always nice</i>
<i>to come home,</i>

00:41.750 --> 00:43.627
fire up the forge,
and think,

00:43.627 --> 00:46.088
<i>"What am I</i>
<i>gonna make tonight?"</i>

00:46.088 --> 00:48.966
<i>‐ My name is Josh Howard, and</i>
<i>I'm from Rogersville, Alabama.</i>

00:48.966 --> 00:51.969
<i>First knife I ever made</i>
<i>was the day after I watched</i>

00:51.969 --> 00:53.595
<i>"Forged in Fire"</i>
<i>for the very first time,</i>

00:53.595 --> 00:55.722
and it was the worst
terrible thing

00:55.722 --> 00:57.516
I've ever seen
in my entire life.

00:57.516 --> 00:59.601
<i>But I was super proud of it.</i>

00:59.601 --> 01:02.020
<i>I want to win this to prove</i>
<i>that you can do anything</i>

01:02.020 --> 01:03.522
<i>you set your mind to</i>

01:03.522 --> 01:05.274
<i>and because my wife</i>
<i>said I had to.</i>

01:05.274 --> 01:06.733
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:06.733 --> 01:08.277
<i>‐ My name's Adam Vormark.</i>

01:08.277 --> 01:10.487
<i>I was born</i>
<i>in Atlanta, Georgia.</i>

01:10.487 --> 01:12.281
<i>Moved around a lot,</i>
<i>my dad was military.</i>

01:12.281 --> 01:15.867
Moved to Egypt and Turkey
for most of my life.

01:15.867 --> 01:17.494
<i>That's where I got to see some</i>

01:17.494 --> 01:19.162
old swordmakers
make some cool stuff,

01:19.162 --> 01:20.706
<i>and that's where my love</i>

01:20.706 --> 01:21.957
for collecting blades started.

01:21.957 --> 01:23.333
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:23.333 --> 01:26.503
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:26.503 --> 01:29.047
You've chosen to pit yourself
against the heat,

01:29.047 --> 01:31.967
the clock, one another,
and, ultimately,

01:31.967 --> 01:34.845
the judges' opinion
in your pursuit of the title

01:34.845 --> 01:37.848
"Forged in Fire" champion
and a check for $10,000.

01:37.848 --> 01:39.683
Let's meet your judges now:

01:39.683 --> 01:42.769
Up first, two‐time "Forged
in Fire" champion Ben Abbott;

01:42.769 --> 01:44.354
up next, historic weapons

01:44.354 --> 01:46.398
re‐creation specialist
David Baker;

01:46.398 --> 01:49.568
and last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:49.568 --> 01:52.070
During my time here
on "Forged in Fire,"

01:52.070 --> 01:54.531
I've been forced to recognize

01:54.531 --> 01:56.408
the elegance
of the simpler things,

01:56.408 --> 01:59.494
like a custom‐made knife
and...

01:59.494 --> 02:01.413
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:01.413 --> 02:02.789
‐ [bleep].

02:02.789 --> 02:04.916
‐ A good shave.

02:04.916 --> 02:07.502
‐ As you can tell,
I don't go to the barbershop.

02:07.502 --> 02:09.171
<i>Lookin' around,</i>
<i>all my other contestants,</i>

02:09.171 --> 02:10.964
<i>they don't go</i>
<i>to the barbershop either.</i>

02:10.964 --> 02:12.674
I think they got
the wrong people.

02:12.674 --> 02:15.886
‐ You'll have to harvest
your canisters

02:15.886 --> 02:17.971
to make a canister
Damascus billet

02:17.971 --> 02:19.723
from this barber's chair.

02:19.723 --> 02:21.642
And then you must fill these
canisters

02:21.642 --> 02:23.560
with items
from our barbershop.

02:23.560 --> 02:26.647
<i>We have straight razors,</i>
<i>box razors, and hair clippers.</i>

02:26.647 --> 02:29.775
<i>You must take steel</i>
<i>from all of those things,</i>

02:29.775 --> 02:33.320
<i>add them to 1095 powder</i>
<i>inside of your canisters</i>

02:33.320 --> 02:35.197
<i>to make that billet,</i>
<i>from which you will forge</i>

02:35.197 --> 02:37.908
<i>a signature blade</i>
<i>in your signature style</i>

02:37.908 --> 02:41.703
<i>between</i>
<i>11 and 13 inches in length.</i>

02:41.703 --> 02:43.664
<i>‐ I felt good</i>
<i>up until right now.</i>

02:43.664 --> 02:46.500
I've never canister Damascus,
let alone using barber tools.

02:46.500 --> 02:48.251
Now I'm just...

02:48.251 --> 02:49.628
I'm kind of scared.

02:49.628 --> 02:51.713
‐ Keep in mind
that in the second round,

02:51.713 --> 02:53.965
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades to turn them

02:53.965 --> 02:56.259
into fully functional weapons
that we will test

02:56.259 --> 02:59.721
for strength and durability
in the coconut chop

02:59.721 --> 03:04.142
and for edge retention
in a horsehair slice.

03:04.142 --> 03:06.144
You have three hours
in the first round

03:06.144 --> 03:07.729
in which to forge your blades.

03:07.729 --> 03:09.314
Keep an eye on your clock.

03:09.314 --> 03:10.982
Pay attention to the details,

03:10.982 --> 03:12.776
because after the time runs out

03:12.776 --> 03:14.736
and the judges
have inspected your work,

03:14.736 --> 03:17.614
one of you will have
to surrender your blade

03:17.614 --> 03:18.865
and leave The Forge.

03:18.865 --> 03:20.033
Good luck, bladesmiths.

03:20.033 --> 03:22.077
Your three hours starts now.

03:22.077 --> 03:23.078
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:23.078 --> 03:24.371
‐ Let's find these canisters.

03:24.371 --> 03:26.164
‐ So we've got these
four bladesmiths

03:26.164 --> 03:28.166
all attacking this
one barber chair,

03:28.166 --> 03:32.421
trying to harvest some
canisters off of that thing.

03:32.421 --> 03:34.214
Those are gonna be
mild steel canisters

03:34.214 --> 03:35.924
that these guys
pull off.

03:35.924 --> 03:37.342
‐ There's two.
‐ There's two.

03:37.342 --> 03:39.177
‐ We're making
canister Damascus steel

03:39.177 --> 03:43.181
<i>using steel canisters,</i>
<i>adding barber's tools</i>

03:43.181 --> 03:46.184
as well as powdered metal,
loading it all together,

03:46.184 --> 03:49.521
and consolidating it
to one solid mass.

03:49.521 --> 03:50.981
<i>‐ So my game plan is</i>

03:50.981 --> 03:52.190
to find out where
the hell I can get

03:52.190 --> 03:54.067
<i>a canister off of this chair.</i>

03:54.067 --> 03:55.318
And I see square tubing
all over the chair,

03:55.318 --> 03:56.945
but everything's chrome,

03:56.945 --> 03:58.280
<i>and I know I don't</i>
<i>want to use that</i>

03:58.280 --> 03:59.906
or burn that off or anything.

03:59.906 --> 04:02.367
I see two canisters
are easy to get to.

04:02.367 --> 04:04.202
So let's get these
bad boys off.

04:04.202 --> 04:07.914
‐ On the foot of the chair
is some nice mild steel.

04:07.914 --> 04:11.460
Looks like it could work well
without any chromium on there,

04:11.460 --> 04:12.919
anything that could
disrupt the weld.

04:12.919 --> 04:14.838
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:14.838 --> 04:16.715
‐ Wow, man, Joe just
grabs a hammer

04:16.715 --> 04:18.842
and harvested steel
like nothin'.

04:18.842 --> 04:20.427
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:20.427 --> 04:22.471
Number two.
Monkey see, monkey do.

04:22.471 --> 04:23.930
Make it happen, cap'n.
Look at that, man.

04:23.930 --> 04:25.557
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:25.557 --> 04:27.476
<i>‐ This is my first time</i>
<i>doing canister Damascus.</i>

04:27.476 --> 04:29.978
I know the basics.

04:29.978 --> 04:32.898
<i>I'm using liquid paper because</i>
<i>it helps keep everything</i>

04:32.898 --> 04:35.567
<i>from sticking to the canister,</i>

04:35.567 --> 04:37.861
but the trick is, I know I
have to let it dry completely.

04:37.861 --> 04:39.738
‐ In a time when I have
all the time

04:39.738 --> 04:41.239
in the world and I
want a pristine billet,

04:41.239 --> 04:42.741
then, yeah,
Wite‐Out is the way to go.

04:42.741 --> 04:44.534
In a timed competition,

04:44.534 --> 04:46.703
often times the best thing
to do is, don't use Wite‐Out.

04:46.703 --> 04:49.039
Let the can weld
to the internal contents

04:49.039 --> 04:51.041
and then just grind away from

04:51.041 --> 04:53.043
the edge and sides
to expose the billet‐‐

04:53.043 --> 04:55.045
‐ That's adding
an entire step in the process.

04:55.045 --> 04:57.506
‐ All right.
Okay, okay.

04:57.506 --> 04:59.299
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:59.299 --> 05:01.259
‐ The piece I'm going
for looks like it's

05:01.259 --> 05:02.719
<i>a structural piece</i>
<i>to this chair.</i>

05:02.719 --> 05:03.845
<i>It's some kind of support.</i>

05:03.845 --> 05:05.347
<i>But it's good, it's thick,</i>

05:05.347 --> 05:07.224
it's heavy wall,
exactly what I need

05:07.224 --> 05:08.266
for a canister weld.

05:08.266 --> 05:10.393
‐ Want me to smash it?

05:10.393 --> 05:12.854
‐ See if you can.
Yeah, go ahead.

05:12.854 --> 05:16.358
‐ Now we've got Josh and Adam

05:16.358 --> 05:19.986
working together to try to peel
those other cans out of there.

05:19.986 --> 05:23.323
‐ My steel is completely
up under this chair.

05:23.323 --> 05:25.534
<i>I have this angle grinder and</i>
<i>I'm trying to get in there,</i>

05:25.534 --> 05:28.161
but it will not fit
where my canister's at,

05:28.161 --> 05:29.329
so I go and grab the torch.

05:29.329 --> 05:30.497
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:30.497 --> 05:32.582
‐ Take that whole block out.

05:32.582 --> 05:35.919
‐ I think Adam is taking on
more of an administrative role.

05:35.919 --> 05:38.088
‐ It is a tight space
up under that chair.

05:38.088 --> 05:40.423
I mean, four hands is probably
two hands too many.

05:40.423 --> 05:41.550
‐ Yeah.

05:41.550 --> 05:42.592
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:42.592 --> 05:44.803
Wow.
‐ Oh, my God!

05:44.803 --> 05:49.558
These vinyl seats are actually
melting and dripping fire.

05:49.558 --> 05:50.976
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:50.976 --> 05:53.103
Harvesting this steel

05:53.103 --> 05:55.856
for Adam and Josh has become
a lot more complicated.

05:55.856 --> 05:58.859
‐ You want to cut that off,
and then we'll flip it over?

05:58.859 --> 06:00.569
‐ I thought they were gonna
scavenge from the chair,

06:00.569 --> 06:02.070
not set it on fire.

06:02.070 --> 06:04.406
‐ I'm setting "Forged in Fire"
on fire.

06:04.406 --> 06:05.615
‐ Talk about a hot seat.

06:05.615 --> 06:07.242
[both laugh]

06:07.242 --> 06:13.123
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:13.123 --> 06:14.124
‐ Take that, Adam‐‐
‐ Are you sure?

06:14.124 --> 06:16.251
‐ Yeah, go ahead.

06:16.251 --> 06:18.628
<i>I finally end up getting</i>
<i>my steel harvested</i>

06:18.628 --> 06:20.422
from this chair
without burning the shop down.

06:20.422 --> 06:22.549
Sorry I got it smoky.

06:22.549 --> 06:24.175
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:24.175 --> 06:26.511
<i>‐ I tried canister Damascus</i>
<i>one time before</i>

06:26.511 --> 06:27.804
<i>and halfway succeeded.</i>

06:27.804 --> 06:29.097
I understand the concept,

06:29.097 --> 06:31.433
but this is gonna test me,
for sure.

06:31.433 --> 06:34.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:34.144 --> 06:36.605
‐ Now the smiths
must use steel

06:36.605 --> 06:38.899
from all the items
in our barber supply shop.

06:38.899 --> 06:41.192
We've got some box razors.

06:41.192 --> 06:43.695
We've also got
some straight razors

06:43.695 --> 06:46.031
and the hair clippers.

06:46.031 --> 06:47.490
Now, the box razors seem

06:47.490 --> 06:48.867
like you just drop
them into the can.

06:48.867 --> 06:50.201
That's great steel.

06:50.201 --> 06:52.245
What about these
hair clippers over here?

06:52.245 --> 06:55.081
The blades look to be
high‐carbon steel.

06:55.081 --> 06:56.791
‐ What about
the straight razor?

06:56.791 --> 06:58.793
‐ You can see machining marks,

06:58.793 --> 07:00.545
so they've been
ground out of a billet

07:00.545 --> 07:02.172
of something pretty hard.

07:02.172 --> 07:03.882
<i>‐ So at this point,</i>
<i>I've got my canister</i>

07:03.882 --> 07:06.760
all packed up nice and tight.
Welds are perfect.

07:06.760 --> 07:08.303
‐ The only thing
that worries me

07:08.303 --> 07:10.764
about Adam is his face fuse.

07:10.764 --> 07:11.806
‐ But look...

07:11.806 --> 07:13.600
if he was gonna be Slick Rick

07:13.600 --> 07:16.645
and test his blade before
that horsehair chop, though...

07:16.645 --> 07:18.813
‐ Ah.
‐ He could just choop!

07:18.813 --> 07:21.191
‐ My beard. Come on,
it speaks for itself, man.

07:21.191 --> 07:22.901
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:22.901 --> 07:25.987
‐ I didn't use the Wite‐Out
inside the canister.

07:25.987 --> 07:29.407
My plan is to keep the mild
steel canister on my blade.

07:29.407 --> 07:31.201
‐ Joe is looking
good right now.

07:31.201 --> 07:32.827
I mean, he's not putting
that Wite‐Out in his can.

07:32.827 --> 07:34.496
It's a very smart way to go.

07:34.496 --> 07:35.789
<i>‐ The anticipation</i>
<i>was killing me,</i>

07:35.789 --> 07:37.165
so it's just nice
to get to work,

07:37.165 --> 07:38.583
get my hands dirty.

07:38.583 --> 07:40.335
<i>‐ First, I have</i>
<i>to Wite‐Out it.</i>

07:40.335 --> 07:43.088
<i>Wite‐Out is gonna keep</i>
<i>the steel from melting</i>

07:43.088 --> 07:44.631
to the canister
so I can peel it off.

07:44.631 --> 07:46.049
Gonna grab me
a handful of these.

07:46.049 --> 07:47.342
Maybe they'll work.

07:47.342 --> 07:48.968
<i>As I'm packing this canister,</i>

07:48.968 --> 07:51.805
I coat the bottom
with 1095 steel powder,

07:51.805 --> 07:53.598
then I throw in some
razor blades

07:53.598 --> 07:55.934
and my clippers
and my straight razor.

07:55.934 --> 07:59.020
Like I'm baking up
a good chili over here.

07:59.020 --> 08:00.814
‐ You gotta really pack
that in because if not,

08:00.814 --> 08:03.692
we're gonna have a lot of space
in there for pockets

08:03.692 --> 08:06.486
to create a lot
of delaminations.

08:06.486 --> 08:08.530
<i>‐ If I win this $10,000,</i>

08:08.530 --> 08:10.031
my wife has been
wanting a new horse barn...

08:10.031 --> 08:12.826
so I think I'm gonna buy
a new power hammer.

08:12.826 --> 08:14.953
‐ Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed!

08:14.953 --> 08:18.039
You have just two hours
remaining to finish your work.

08:18.039 --> 08:19.624
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

08:19.624 --> 08:21.376
‐ This canister challenge comes

08:21.376 --> 08:23.002
down to two things,
in my opinion:

08:23.002 --> 08:24.587
it come down to heat
of the can

08:24.587 --> 08:26.005
when you go to the press

08:26.005 --> 08:28.842
and how you actually
use that press.

08:28.842 --> 08:31.553
‐ You're squeezing
180 degrees in direction,

08:31.553 --> 08:33.471
<i>and you've got to make sure</i>
<i>you do it all equally,</i>

08:33.471 --> 08:35.890
and you have to make sure
you do it when it's hot.

08:35.890 --> 08:38.309
<i>As a bonus, you don't know</i>
<i>if it's right</i>

08:38.309 --> 08:40.228
because you can't see it.
It's in a can.

08:40.228 --> 08:42.731
<i>You're just hoping</i>
<i>and you are praying</i>

08:42.731 --> 08:45.150
<i>that this is gonna</i>
<i>come out like you need:</i>

08:45.150 --> 08:47.444
no cracks, no shunts,
nothing.

08:47.444 --> 08:48.653
All right.

08:49.654 --> 08:51.823
‐ [bleep], that's ugly.

08:51.823 --> 08:53.575
<i>I notice as</i>
<i>I'm using the press,</i>

08:53.575 --> 08:55.326
<i>the front half of the billet</i>

08:55.326 --> 08:58.288
is working a little easier
than the back half,

08:58.288 --> 09:00.874
<i>so I'm worried that</i>
<i>the front half</i>

09:00.874 --> 09:03.585
<i>is not welded up</i>
<i>and the back half is...</i>

09:03.585 --> 09:05.128
[bleep].
<i>Which could leave me</i>

09:05.128 --> 09:06.588
<i>with enough material</i>
<i>to make a blade</i>

09:06.588 --> 09:09.716
and sacrifice the front half
or not. [laughs]

09:09.716 --> 09:11.426
Whoo!

09:11.426 --> 09:12.635
But I'm really hoping that
this canister I've got

09:12.635 --> 09:13.970
yields enough of a solid billet

09:13.970 --> 09:15.555
that I can work a blade
out of it.

09:15.555 --> 09:16.806
<i>I just keep moving it</i>
<i>back and forth.</i>

09:16.806 --> 09:18.767
Let's hope it works.

09:18.767 --> 09:21.144
<i>‐ I'm feeling pretty confident</i>
<i>that I have the thing,</i>

09:21.144 --> 09:22.520
<i>you know,</i>
<i>to welding temperature</i>

09:22.520 --> 09:24.064
<i>all the way through,</i>

09:24.064 --> 09:26.274
and then I go
to the power hammer with it.

09:26.274 --> 09:28.276
Wow, that thing moves metal.

09:28.276 --> 09:31.613
<i>I got an old 1920s</i>
<i>crank‐actuated hammer.</i>

09:31.613 --> 09:33.156
It's like
you drive your buddy's car

09:33.156 --> 09:34.157
and it's way nicer than yours.

09:34.157 --> 09:36.201
Now you want a new car.

09:36.201 --> 09:37.744
‐ Now, Joe's the only one
of our smiths

09:37.744 --> 09:39.621
that didn't use Wite‐Out,

09:39.621 --> 09:43.541
so he's just drawing that can
out right on the material

09:43.541 --> 09:45.710
and saved himself that step.

09:47.796 --> 09:49.297
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

09:49.297 --> 09:51.508
‐ That's what you wanna see.

09:51.508 --> 09:52.967
<i>Now that I got my can off,</i>

09:52.967 --> 09:55.303
I'm gonna start drawing
this billet out,

09:55.303 --> 09:57.806
working it slow,
trying to keep any cracks out.

09:57.806 --> 10:00.100
‐ Josh has a nice bar of butter

10:00.100 --> 10:02.685
that he's just putting
into that press right now, man.

10:02.685 --> 10:05.063
‐ Nice color.
‐ It's nice and even.

10:05.063 --> 10:07.440
‐ But I'm drawing
my steel out too far.

10:07.440 --> 10:10.151
‐ Josh is at the point
of the process where

10:10.151 --> 10:11.778
he really needs to decide
how wide he wants

10:11.778 --> 10:13.446
that blade to be,

10:13.446 --> 10:15.281
and fuller that material
out before he draws it out.

10:15.281 --> 10:16.324
‐ Yeah.

10:16.324 --> 10:17.617
‐ I've got the billet made.

10:17.617 --> 10:19.661
I just gotta forge
a knife out now.

10:19.661 --> 10:23.039
‐ Bladesmiths,
two hours has elapsed!

10:23.039 --> 10:25.625
‐ Yeah, now it's coming free.

10:25.625 --> 10:27.210
<i>I get my canister off.</i>

10:27.210 --> 10:28.711
<i>Now it's time to work</i>
<i>this material</i>

10:28.711 --> 10:30.505
<i>and hammer it down</i>
<i>into something</i>

10:30.505 --> 10:31.589
that we can recognize.

10:33.133 --> 10:35.093
‐ There's a problem
with Benton's billet.

10:36.886 --> 10:38.221
<i>My stomach drops.</i>

10:38.221 --> 10:39.681
<i>For all I know,</i>
<i>these cracks</i>

10:39.681 --> 10:41.683
could go all the way
through my billet.

10:41.683 --> 10:43.393
‐ Looks like Benton and Adam

10:43.393 --> 10:46.312
are dealing with cracks
in their billet right now.

10:46.312 --> 10:50.483
<i>‐ I notice quite a number</i>
<i>of very large cracks,</i>

10:50.483 --> 10:51.985
and that's just not good.

10:51.985 --> 10:53.611
‐ Right there.
‐ Oh, no.

10:53.611 --> 10:55.238
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

10:55.238 --> 10:56.739
<i>‐ If I try to pound a blade</i>

10:56.739 --> 10:58.283
<i>out of this</i>
<i>and I don't fix it,</i>

10:58.283 --> 11:01.452
it's just gonna crack in half.

11:01.452 --> 11:04.497
‐ I think Adam is, right now,
at the decision point.

11:04.497 --> 11:06.374
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:06.374 --> 11:08.042
<i>‐ At this point,</i>
<i>I have two options:</i>

11:08.042 --> 11:10.879
<i>I can cut these,</i>
<i>grind them flat, stack them,</i>

11:10.879 --> 11:12.755
and weld into another billet

11:12.755 --> 11:14.299
or just make another canister.

11:14.299 --> 11:16.843
‐ Hopefully,
Adam sorts this out.

11:16.843 --> 11:19.554
‐ Got a lot of work to do.
Got less than an hour to do it.

11:19.554 --> 11:21.181
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:21.181 --> 11:22.724
<i>‐ They're pretty bad.</i>

11:22.724 --> 11:24.058
<i>I can get a finished knife</i>

11:24.058 --> 11:25.268
with a crack
right down the middle.

11:26.603 --> 11:28.521
‐ The surf

11:28.521 --> 11:30.815
<i>The only thing I can think</i>
<i>of is, I know an old trick</i>

11:30.815 --> 11:34.694
involving powder, steel,
or metal flakes to fill voids.

11:34.694 --> 11:36.779
‐ That's a great idea because
a little bit of hand hammering,

11:36.779 --> 11:39.908
you can try and consolidate
those cracks back together.

11:39.908 --> 11:41.242
<i>‐ It works in theory,</i>

11:41.242 --> 11:42.911
and I hope that it works
for this too.

11:42.911 --> 11:45.538
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:45.538 --> 11:48.208
<i>‐ There are some serious</i>
<i>deep cracks in my billet.</i>

11:48.208 --> 11:50.293
If I try to pound
a blade out of this

11:50.293 --> 11:52.962
and I don't fix it,
it's just gonna crack in half.

11:52.962 --> 11:54.923
I'm gonna have to restart.

11:54.923 --> 11:56.591
<i>Time's running out.</i>
<i>I need to hurry up.</i>

11:56.591 --> 11:59.469
I can't afford
to take anything slow.

11:59.469 --> 12:00.887
‐ Oh, it's still wet.

12:00.887 --> 12:02.138
The powder is gonna get

12:02.138 --> 12:03.264
incorporated
with the Wite‐Out.

12:03.264 --> 12:04.891
It's gonna become this slurry,

12:04.891 --> 12:07.936
a coating of stuff
that won't weld to itself,

12:07.936 --> 12:09.520
probably will weld to the can,

12:09.520 --> 12:11.731
does everything wrong
with the process.

12:11.731 --> 12:12.941
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:12.941 --> 12:14.317
[all shouting]

12:14.317 --> 12:16.444
‐ Man. It's like somebody
threw a handful

12:16.444 --> 12:17.695
of gunpower in there.

12:17.695 --> 12:18.780
‐ [sighs]

12:18.780 --> 12:20.281
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:20.281 --> 12:21.908
<i>‐ My blade's</i>
<i>coming out to shape</i>

12:21.908 --> 12:23.159
and I'm starting
to feel good.

12:23.159 --> 12:25.954
<i>I go ahead and I quench it,</i>

12:25.954 --> 12:27.413
<i>file test</i>
<i>to make sure it's hard.</i>

12:27.413 --> 12:30.583
Ooh. That's not very hard.

12:30.583 --> 12:31.584
Do it again.

12:31.584 --> 12:36.256
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:36.256 --> 12:37.715
Still grabbing.

12:37.715 --> 12:39.300
It dawns on me.

12:39.300 --> 12:41.469
I forgot that, yeah,
it's coated in mild steel,

12:41.469 --> 12:42.929
so it didn't harden.

12:42.929 --> 12:45.848
The softness
is due to the canister.

12:45.848 --> 12:47.600
There it is.

12:49.644 --> 12:51.104
‐ I am running out of time.

12:51.104 --> 12:52.772
<i>I'm making a chopper</i>

12:52.772 --> 12:54.357
<i>and this thing is thick</i>

12:54.357 --> 12:56.651
and I need to curve it
so I can forge a bevel.

12:56.651 --> 12:59.654
So the easiest way
to do this is just to start

12:59.654 --> 13:02.031
smacking it on the horn.

13:02.031 --> 13:04.284
‐ His profile
is really coming along,

13:04.284 --> 13:05.535
just putting a little
bit of curvature in there.

13:05.535 --> 13:06.995
‐ That'll work.

13:06.995 --> 13:09.038
‐ I just hope that
all those surface cracks

13:09.038 --> 13:10.623
he was chasing
earlier are gone.

13:10.623 --> 13:15.545
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:15.545 --> 13:17.213
‐ So I get my blade finished,
ground out,

13:17.213 --> 13:19.716
<i>and I've got to get</i>
<i>this blade in the oil.</i>

13:19.716 --> 13:20.800
Quenching!

13:20.800 --> 13:25.388
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:25.388 --> 13:27.223
‐ Man, that looks like
a nice, straight blade.

13:27.223 --> 13:28.808
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

13:28.808 --> 13:30.476
<i>‐ It looks good.</i>
<i>It's pretty straight.</i>

13:30.476 --> 13:31.978
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:31.978 --> 13:33.021
But it's not hard,
so I gotta go

13:33.021 --> 13:34.564
back in the forge.

13:34.564 --> 13:36.983
I don't think
I went hot enough with it.

13:36.983 --> 13:38.818
<i>Any time you go</i>
<i>back in the forge,</i>

13:38.818 --> 13:41.154
you're putting so much
stress in that blade.

13:41.154 --> 13:43.197
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

13:43.197 --> 13:44.574
I get my blade out this time.

13:44.574 --> 13:45.742
<i>It's hard.</i>

13:45.742 --> 13:46.868
I'll buy that.

13:46.868 --> 13:49.996
‐ Ten minutes, bladesmiths!

13:49.996 --> 13:51.039
‐ Joe is over
in the acid over there.

13:51.039 --> 13:52.832
‐ Excellent.

13:52.832 --> 13:54.709
<i>‐ The last step is</i>
<i>getting it to the acid to etch</i>

13:54.709 --> 13:56.753
and see what I got.

13:56.753 --> 13:58.254
<i>And, sure enough,</i>
<i>I can see the, like,</i>

13:58.254 --> 14:00.298
little teeth on the clippers
in my blade.

14:00.298 --> 14:02.800
I can distinguish
what's a razor and whatnot.

14:02.800 --> 14:04.677
<i>I'm feeling pretty good.</i>

14:04.677 --> 14:06.512
<i>It looks like I have</i>
<i>my hardened steel on the edge.</i>

14:06.512 --> 14:09.015
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:09.015 --> 14:11.017
‐ I've got a little less than
ten minutes to finish this,

14:11.017 --> 14:12.852
and I haven't even cut
the can off yet.

14:12.852 --> 14:14.562
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:14.562 --> 14:16.272
‐ I'm hoping that
Adam takes care,

14:16.272 --> 14:18.733
'cause now is the time
where you smash you hand,

14:18.733 --> 14:20.985
you make mistakes,
you hurt yourself.

14:20.985 --> 14:22.695
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:22.695 --> 14:24.572
<i>‐ For some reason,</i>
<i>unlike the first billet,</i>

14:24.572 --> 14:27.158
there is a patch
about 4 inches wide

14:27.158 --> 14:29.786
that has welded
to the canister material.

14:29.786 --> 14:31.079
[bleep].

14:31.079 --> 14:34.624
I just watch
the time just disappear.

14:34.624 --> 14:36.459
<i>I may not get a full blade,</i>

14:36.459 --> 14:38.044
<i>but I'm gonna</i>
<i>bust my ass trying.</i>

14:38.044 --> 14:39.587
This steel
isn't gonna beat me.

14:39.587 --> 14:41.672
[bleep].
‐ Come on, kid, keep working.

14:41.672 --> 14:44.258
<i>‐ I just do not have the time</i>
<i>to put it back in the forge</i>

14:44.258 --> 14:46.427
<i>until this</i>
<i>canister section is off.</i>

14:46.427 --> 14:49.222
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:49.222 --> 14:50.223
[all cheering]

14:50.223 --> 14:51.224
‐ There we go!

14:51.224 --> 14:53.059
‐ Whoo‐hoo!

14:53.059 --> 14:55.103
<i>Just in the nick of time,</i>
<i>billet falls out.</i>

14:55.103 --> 14:56.229
Suck it, bar.

14:56.229 --> 15:01.359
‐ Five, four, three, two, one.

15:01.359 --> 15:02.902
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines!

15:02.902 --> 15:04.320
Drop your tools.

15:04.320 --> 15:07.406
This first round
of competition is over.

15:07.406 --> 15:09.075
[applause]

15:09.075 --> 15:10.535
‐ That was hard‐fought, man.

15:10.535 --> 15:12.245
‐ Oh, my God.

15:12.245 --> 15:13.955
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:13.955 --> 15:15.456
‐ Bladesmiths,
in the first round of

15:15.456 --> 15:17.458
our barbershop‐inspired
competition,

15:17.458 --> 15:20.920
we asked each of you
to harvest a mild steel can

15:20.920 --> 15:22.630
from this barbershop chair

15:22.630 --> 15:24.757
and combine that
with the steels

15:24.757 --> 15:26.843
from our barbershop
supply station

15:26.843 --> 15:29.887
with 1095 powder
to make a Damascus billet

15:29.887 --> 15:33.015
from which to forge
an 11‐ to 13‐inch blade

15:33.015 --> 15:35.184
in your signature style.

15:35.184 --> 15:37.103
Now, let's not split
any hairs about this.

15:37.103 --> 15:39.814
There's a problem
out there on The Forge floor.

15:39.814 --> 15:44.944
Adam, I commend you, man,
for battling as hard as you did

15:44.944 --> 15:47.822
to come up with what you've got
there on your anvil.

15:47.822 --> 15:51.784
You worked until
the very last second.

15:51.784 --> 15:53.703
But, unfortunately,
what you have is

15:53.703 --> 15:55.621
a clean 9‐inch billet.

15:55.621 --> 15:58.166
It is not a blade,
and it's not heat‐treated.

15:58.166 --> 16:00.126
And for that reason,
I have to ask you

16:00.126 --> 16:02.587
to please leave The Forge.

16:02.587 --> 16:04.297
<i>‐ The competition</i>
<i>was pretty tough.</i>

16:04.297 --> 16:06.299
I am tired, especially
after beating on that

16:06.299 --> 16:07.633
billet so long,
but, you know,

16:07.633 --> 16:09.051
<i>who doesn't love some cardio?</i>

16:09.051 --> 16:10.303
<i>I may not have won</i>
<i>the competition,</i>

16:10.303 --> 16:11.804
<i>but I'm very proud of myself.</i>

16:11.804 --> 16:12.930
Can't to go home
and see my daughter.

16:12.930 --> 16:14.473
[laughs]

16:14.473 --> 16:17.226
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:17.226 --> 16:19.687
‐ Bladesmiths,
Adam's out of this competition.

16:19.687 --> 16:21.564
That doesn't mean that
you guys get a free pass.

16:21.564 --> 16:23.482
You still have to make
the parameters

16:23.482 --> 16:25.651
and listen to what the judges
have to say about your work.

16:25.651 --> 16:27.153
Joe, you're up first.

16:27.153 --> 16:28.863
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:28.863 --> 16:35.912
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:37.914 --> 16:38.915
‐ Where is your knife?

16:38.915 --> 16:40.124
[laughter]

16:40.124 --> 16:42.335
Oh, it's right here.

16:42.335 --> 16:44.212
‐ He likes it.
‐ I'm in love.

16:44.212 --> 16:48.424
From the shape, the scale,
the way it feels in the hand.

16:48.424 --> 16:49.425
Don't mess this up.

16:49.425 --> 16:50.760
[laughter]

16:50.760 --> 16:52.720
‐ I'll try not to.
‐ All right.

16:52.720 --> 16:56.098
<i>Leave it as is</i>
<i>and just beautify it, but...</i>

16:56.098 --> 16:57.391
all I can say is wow.
Well done.

16:57.391 --> 16:58.601
‐ Thank you so much.

16:58.601 --> 17:00.019
‐ All right, Benton, you're up.

17:00.019 --> 17:02.188
Please present
your steel to the judges.

17:02.188 --> 17:04.065
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:04.065 --> 17:05.691
<i>‐ Well, Benton,</i>
<i>first thing that I feel</i>

17:05.691 --> 17:07.318
<i>as I pick this knife</i>
<i>up is the weight.</i>

17:07.318 --> 17:09.278
There's a lot of mass here.

17:09.278 --> 17:12.615
But the second thing that I see
is, there's surface cracking.

17:12.615 --> 17:14.784
A crack on the surface
can lead to a break.

17:14.784 --> 17:16.410
It is an important
thing to take care of,

17:16.410 --> 17:19.538
but I think you have
enough mass here to do it.

17:19.538 --> 17:21.666
So I think you're well
on your way.

17:21.666 --> 17:23.125
‐ Thank you.
‐ Josh, you're up.

17:23.125 --> 17:24.585
Please present
your blade to the judges.

17:24.585 --> 17:26.504
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:26.504 --> 17:29.882
‐ So when I look at this,
that's really cool.

17:29.882 --> 17:32.927
And that's really big.

17:32.927 --> 17:35.263
Your ricasso
is almost an inch long,

17:35.263 --> 17:36.889
then you've got a finger weld,

17:36.889 --> 17:39.267
then you've got
a whole handle behind that.

17:39.267 --> 17:41.018
Literally, from the blade,
you've got

17:41.018 --> 17:42.645
a sold hand and a half
handle here.

17:42.645 --> 17:43.980
Having said that,

17:43.980 --> 17:45.898
if this whole thing
were smaller

17:45.898 --> 17:47.608
and that same shape,

17:47.608 --> 17:49.193
I think it's a really
attractive shape.

17:49.193 --> 17:50.778
Nicely done.
‐ Thank you.

17:50.778 --> 17:52.697
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:52.697 --> 17:54.740
‐ Bladesmiths, congratulations.
You all passed parameters,

17:54.740 --> 17:57.368
which passes you into this
next round of competition.

17:57.368 --> 17:59.245
Now in this round,
you'll make those blades

17:59.245 --> 18:01.747
fully functional by attaching
handles to them.

18:01.747 --> 18:04.166
You'll have two hours
in which to complete your work

18:04.166 --> 18:05.835
addressing the flaws and issues

18:05.835 --> 18:07.420
that were identified
in your blades and attaching

18:07.420 --> 18:09.088
those handles so that
we can test them

18:09.088 --> 18:13.050
for strength and durability
in our coconut chop

18:13.050 --> 18:17.138
and for edge retention
in that horsehair slice.

18:17.138 --> 18:18.848
I remind you that
after the weapons are tested,

18:18.848 --> 18:21.142
one of you will be selected
to turn in your blade

18:21.142 --> 18:22.435
and leave The Forge.

18:22.435 --> 18:25.104
Good luck.
Your two hours starts...

18:25.104 --> 18:26.147
now.

18:26.147 --> 18:28.941
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:28.941 --> 18:30.276
<i>‐ The judges said</i>
<i>my handle's too long.</i>

18:30.276 --> 18:31.944
The first thing
I wanna do is,

18:31.944 --> 18:33.321
I'm gonna cut
the length down on my handle.

18:33.321 --> 18:34.780
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:34.780 --> 18:36.949
‐ Josh has that
really long handle

18:36.949 --> 18:40.870
on a very, I don't know,
straight razor‐like blade.

18:40.870 --> 18:43.998
I prefer to have a handle
that isn't confusing.

18:43.998 --> 18:46.208
You know exactly where
to put every finger,

18:46.208 --> 18:48.628
and when you put them there,
it feels comfortable.

18:48.628 --> 18:50.796
<i>‐ I'll take the material</i>
<i>from the end of my handle.</i>

18:50.796 --> 18:53.215
That way, I know I'm not
gonna mess my blade at all.

18:53.215 --> 18:54.967
I think they'll be pleased
with it now.

18:54.967 --> 18:57.053
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:57.053 --> 19:00.014
<i>‐ Doug's feedback was really,</i>
<i>really positive,</i>

19:00.014 --> 19:04.018
so it's just a matter of not
making any big mistakes.

19:04.018 --> 19:06.979
The first thing I do
is select my handle material.

19:06.979 --> 19:09.231
I'm gonna take both of these,
see what happens.

19:09.231 --> 19:11.567
Before I even think
about constructing my handle,

19:11.567 --> 19:13.861
I gotta make sure the surfaces
are nice and tight

19:13.861 --> 19:16.322
and good contact area.

19:16.322 --> 19:19.700
<i>So I start refining my blade</i>
<i>geometry in the finish.</i>

19:19.700 --> 19:21.661
‐ How much of this
could Joe be doing

19:21.661 --> 19:22.745
with his handle already on?

19:22.745 --> 19:24.538
Get that stuff out of the way

19:24.538 --> 19:26.666
and then go back to the grinder
and finish your grinding.

19:26.666 --> 19:28.668
<i>‐ I want to stay focused</i>
<i>and be methodical,</i>

19:28.668 --> 19:29.835
but I don't want
to lose myself

19:29.835 --> 19:31.337
and get too deep into that

19:31.337 --> 19:33.714
and then end up with not
enough time to finish.

19:33.714 --> 19:37.176
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:37.176 --> 19:38.260
‐ Benton's got
the most work to do.

19:38.260 --> 19:39.720
He's got the thickest blade.

19:39.720 --> 19:42.139
He's got the most
surface cracking.

19:42.139 --> 19:44.350
‐ I need to really reduce
my mass and my blade profile

19:44.350 --> 19:45.768
and lighten it up,

19:45.768 --> 19:47.520
and I really gotta get
these cracks out.

19:47.520 --> 19:49.939
Luckily, there's one solution
for both of my issues,

19:49.939 --> 19:52.191
and I just have to grind
and reduce stock.

19:52.191 --> 19:53.526
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:53.526 --> 19:54.860
‐ It's good to see Benton

19:54.860 --> 19:57.863
aggressively hogging
that steel.

19:57.863 --> 19:58.906
‐ Everything is going great.

19:58.906 --> 20:01.075
[laughs]
Yeah, baby.

20:01.075 --> 20:03.035
<i>All my surface cracks</i>
<i>are grinding out.</i>

20:03.035 --> 20:05.037
They don't travel
through the blade.

20:05.037 --> 20:07.248
And then I see it.

20:07.248 --> 20:08.082
I see the crack.

20:12.378 --> 20:15.089
<i>I can either try</i>
<i>to grind one side</i>

20:15.089 --> 20:16.757
<i>and have a little bit</i>
<i>of a crooked edge</i>

20:16.757 --> 20:18.259
<i>to grind this crack out,</i>

20:18.259 --> 20:22.388
or I can completely
reprofile my blade.

20:22.388 --> 20:24.890
I choose to do
a little bit of both,

20:24.890 --> 20:27.393
<i>but I have to grind</i>
<i>this thing very fast</i>

20:27.393 --> 20:29.854
so I can get to everything
else that I need to do.

20:29.854 --> 20:31.564
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:31.564 --> 20:35.359
‐ Bladesmiths, you have
just one hour remaining!

20:35.359 --> 20:37.945
<i>‐ I get to the pantry</i>
<i>and I find some ironwood,</i>

20:37.945 --> 20:41.073
so that clock's still ticking
and I don't have any pin holes.

20:41.073 --> 20:42.742
Where's the drill press?

20:42.742 --> 20:43.909
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:43.909 --> 20:46.996
Come on, baby, cut.

20:46.996 --> 20:48.038
Yeah.

20:48.038 --> 20:49.915
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:49.915 --> 20:51.625
‐ The pins are a bit short.

20:51.625 --> 20:53.085
‐ So do you expect that Josh

20:53.085 --> 20:55.087
is just gonna grind
down to that end...

20:55.087 --> 20:56.422
‐ Right.
‐ Sunk a little too deeply.

20:56.422 --> 20:57.923
‐ Which unfortunately

20:57.923 --> 20:59.759
dictates the shape
of his knife handle.

20:59.759 --> 21:01.635
‐ I'm working on getting
my pins aligned

21:01.635 --> 21:03.137
'cause one of them's
a little bit short,

21:03.137 --> 21:04.680
so I'm pushing it through

21:04.680 --> 21:06.557
'cause I wanna take
a bunch of this off.

21:06.557 --> 21:09.101
I've gotta make this thing
go through a coconut

21:09.101 --> 21:10.603
and then some horsehair.

21:10.603 --> 21:12.438
My wife raises horses.
I know all about cutting

21:12.438 --> 21:14.273
horsehair 'cause
when she's not looking,

21:14.273 --> 21:18.527
I'll trim some off her horse's
tail just to make her mad.

21:18.527 --> 21:20.404
‐ I spent way too much time
at this grinder,

21:20.404 --> 21:22.323
and now it's go time.

21:22.323 --> 21:24.116
‐ There we go,
Joe to the drill.

21:24.116 --> 21:26.494
‐ Now I gotta get holes
in my scales that line up.

21:26.494 --> 21:27.953
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:27.953 --> 21:29.622
What the heck?

21:29.622 --> 21:31.791
Getting my holes lined up was
a little stressful,

21:31.791 --> 21:33.793
and I'm running around,
getting tools,

21:33.793 --> 21:37.087
<i>and my plan's changing</i>
<i>as I go a little bit.</i>

21:37.087 --> 21:38.506
Pins are too big.

21:38.506 --> 21:40.424
Now I'm starting to rush.

21:40.424 --> 21:42.426
<i>Having 40 minutes</i>
<i>to sculpt the handle,</i>

21:42.426 --> 21:44.553
<i>it's gonna have all</i>
<i>these facets.</i>

21:44.553 --> 21:46.639
Good indexing and not having
any hot spots

21:46.639 --> 21:49.767
is not something
that is easily achievable.

21:49.767 --> 21:51.352
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:51.352 --> 21:53.354
‐ 30 minutes, bladesmiths!

21:53.354 --> 21:54.814
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:54.814 --> 21:56.774
‐ So I finish
reprofiling my blade,

21:56.774 --> 21:59.443
but I feel like
I'm a step behind.

21:59.443 --> 22:01.445
<i>I need to have</i>
<i>a contoured handle</i>

22:01.445 --> 22:04.240
that the judges can
hold onto and hang onto.

22:04.240 --> 22:06.867
<i>I only have less than</i>
<i>30 minutes left.</i>

22:06.867 --> 22:08.285
I mean, it's not
gonna be perfect.

22:08.285 --> 22:10.621
So I decide to go
with linen Micarta.

22:10.621 --> 22:11.872
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:11.872 --> 22:14.041
‐ It grinds well.
It shapes well.

22:14.041 --> 22:16.293
It glues well.
It's a great handle material.

22:16.293 --> 22:19.505
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:19.505 --> 22:21.006
‐ It's very important
to get this handle shaped

22:21.006 --> 22:22.341
where it feels good
for the judges,

22:22.341 --> 22:24.051
'cause if I'm gonna
get sent home,

22:24.051 --> 22:27.179
I don't want it to be
for an uncomfortable handle.

22:27.179 --> 22:29.390
<i>I want it really nice</i>
<i>and curved</i>

22:29.390 --> 22:31.392
so that it fits really
good in your hands.

22:31.392 --> 22:33.978
‐ I hope that it's
just deceptive,

22:33.978 --> 22:35.563
and then it looks
like it's skinny.

22:35.563 --> 22:37.523
‐ I'd say other than breaks,

22:37.523 --> 22:39.692
handles send more smiths home
than anything else.

22:39.692 --> 22:42.236
‐ I keep working that
down until it feels perfect.

22:42.236 --> 22:43.904
Ah, there we go.

22:43.904 --> 22:45.030
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:45.030 --> 22:47.074
‐ With about ten minutes to go,

22:47.074 --> 22:48.784
<i>I begin etching the blade.</i>

22:48.784 --> 22:50.703
<i>The longer I leave</i>
<i>the blade in acid,</i>

22:50.703 --> 22:52.079
<i>the more contrast</i>
<i>I'm gonna get</i>

22:52.079 --> 22:53.539
in the patterning
of the blade.

22:53.539 --> 22:56.041
‐ One thing that
I like about Damascus

22:56.041 --> 22:57.668
is that it's like
a fingerprint.

22:57.668 --> 23:01.255
No two Damascus patterns
are exactly alike.

23:01.255 --> 23:03.048
‐ So far, so good.

23:03.048 --> 23:04.842
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:04.842 --> 23:06.343
<i>‐ Originally,</i>
<i>I wanted to be sharpening</i>

23:06.343 --> 23:08.262
my blade with 30 minutes left,

23:08.262 --> 23:11.557
but I look up at the clock
and I've got 3 minutes left.

23:11.557 --> 23:13.225
‐ Benton's up underneath
the grinder

23:13.225 --> 23:15.019
on the slack underneath.

23:15.019 --> 23:16.520
‐ It's a good strategy
'cause it gives you that

23:16.520 --> 23:17.855
apple seed edge we like.

23:17.855 --> 23:19.064
You know, it's not
a faceted edge.

23:19.064 --> 23:20.649
It kind of comes
out Gothic arch,

23:20.649 --> 23:21.734
which is a stronger edge.

23:21.734 --> 23:23.694
‐ I only have seconds left.

23:23.694 --> 23:25.738
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:25.738 --> 23:31.035
‐ Five, four, three, two, one.

23:31.035 --> 23:32.995
‐ Bladesmiths, drop your tools.
Stop what you're doing.

23:32.995 --> 23:35.080
This second round
of competition is over!

23:35.080 --> 23:36.582
[applause]

23:36.582 --> 23:38.542
<i>‐ I think my blade's</i>
<i>good enough,</i>

23:38.542 --> 23:42.463
but I'm not quite so sure it's
as sharp as it needs to be.

23:42.463 --> 23:44.381
But I did my best.

23:44.381 --> 23:45.966
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:45.966 --> 23:47.593
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to the strength test.

23:47.593 --> 23:49.637
To test the strength
and durability of your edge

23:49.637 --> 23:51.430
as well as your overall
construction of your knives,

23:51.430 --> 23:53.265
I'm going to be bashing
them mercilessly

23:53.265 --> 23:55.851
into these poor,
unsuspecting coconuts.

23:55.851 --> 23:57.436
I'm gonna hit
each coconut once.

23:57.436 --> 23:58.771
If it's not obliterated,

23:58.771 --> 24:00.773
I'm gonna take
another chop at it.

24:00.773 --> 24:02.149
Joe, you're up first.
You ready?

24:02.149 --> 24:04.109
‐ I'm ready.
‐ All right.

24:04.109 --> 24:06.445
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:06.445 --> 24:08.405
<i>‐ Coconuts are pretty hard</i>
<i>on a fine edge</i>

24:08.405 --> 24:10.282
<i>that's also capable</i>
<i>of cutting horsehair.</i>

24:10.282 --> 24:12.493
This is pretty nerve‐racking,
you know?

24:12.493 --> 24:14.244
<i>The heart is pumping.</i>

24:14.244 --> 24:17.414
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:17.414 --> 24:18.415
[whistles]

24:18.415 --> 24:23.462
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:23.462 --> 24:25.172
‐ That's crazy.

24:25.172 --> 24:28.592
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:28.592 --> 24:31.971
Nice.
‐ Wow.

24:31.971 --> 24:33.138
‐ Well, Joe,

24:33.138 --> 24:34.473
this handle is awesome.

24:34.473 --> 24:35.808
I mean, it's really
comfortable.

24:35.808 --> 24:37.393
It fits well in my hand.

24:37.393 --> 24:39.937
Your knife is still sharp,
still straight.

24:39.937 --> 24:41.480
Well done.
‐ Thank you.

24:41.480 --> 24:43.941
‐ Benton, you're up next.
You ready for this?

24:43.941 --> 24:45.275
‐ Let's do it.
‐ All right.

24:45.275 --> 24:47.611
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:47.611 --> 24:49.488
<i>‐ Ben has my blade</i>
<i>in his hand</i>

24:49.488 --> 24:51.657
<i>and I see him turn</i>
<i>it over numerous times</i>

24:51.657 --> 24:53.617
<i>and I think to myself,</i>

24:53.617 --> 24:56.537
<i>"He is seeing every single</i>
<i>microscopic flaw possible."</i>

24:56.537 --> 24:58.580
<i>My blade has a lot</i>
<i>of surface cracks.</i>

24:58.580 --> 25:00.082
I am terrified.

25:00.708 --> 25:02.501
<i>I really.</i>

25:02.501 --> 25:04.586
And I just want this thing
to do what I built it to do.

25:04.586 --> 25:11.593
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:21.353 --> 25:23.022
‐ Well, Benton,
first things first:

25:23.022 --> 25:25.733
your edge held up well.
I don't see any evidence

25:25.733 --> 25:27.359
of any chipping or rolling
or anything like that.

25:27.359 --> 25:28.944
It's still straight.

25:28.944 --> 25:31.822
All told, your knife
survived really well.

25:31.822 --> 25:33.699
Well done.
‐ Thank you.

25:33.699 --> 25:35.075
‐ Josh, you're up next.
You ready?

25:35.075 --> 25:37.619
‐ Let it rip.
‐ All right.

25:37.619 --> 25:39.705
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:39.705 --> 25:42.041
<i>‐ Watching Joe and Benton</i>
<i>get through their coconuts</i>

25:42.041 --> 25:43.959
<i>without any problem,</i>
<i>pressure's on.</i>

25:43.959 --> 25:45.377
<i>I am nervous.</i>

25:45.377 --> 25:47.212
Is my blade as good
as it could be?

25:47.212 --> 25:49.882
No, I could definitely
make it a lot better,

25:49.882 --> 25:51.717
<i>but we'll see how it does.</i>

25:51.717 --> 25:58.766
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:07.232 --> 26:08.901
‐ Well, Josh,
first things first:

26:08.901 --> 26:10.360
your edge held up really well.

26:10.360 --> 26:12.279
It's still as sharp
as when you made it.

26:12.279 --> 26:13.906
It's a very stout edge,

26:13.906 --> 26:15.783
so it'll hold up well
on coconuts.

26:15.783 --> 26:18.452
We'll see how it does
against horsehair.

26:18.452 --> 26:19.912
The main thing that
jumps out at me, though,

26:19.912 --> 26:21.955
is this handle spindly.
It's small.

26:21.955 --> 26:24.249
For a big chopping blade
like this,

26:24.249 --> 26:26.919
I'd like to have a little more
handle there to hold onto.

26:26.919 --> 26:30.881
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:30.881 --> 26:34.259
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
this is the sharpness test,

26:34.259 --> 26:36.595
the horsehair slice.

26:36.595 --> 26:40.099
A sharp blade should give
it a good cut and trim.

26:40.099 --> 26:42.601
A dull one, well,
it just might push it aside,

26:42.601 --> 26:45.479
distress it,
or, worse, just pull it.

26:45.479 --> 26:47.147
Joe, you're up first.
You ready for this?

26:47.147 --> 26:48.857
‐ I am.
‐ Let's do this.

26:48.857 --> 26:55.864
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:00.994 --> 27:02.204
‐ [whistles]

27:02.204 --> 27:06.875
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:06.875 --> 27:10.462
‐ All right, Joe,
your edge gave it a trim.

27:10.462 --> 27:12.464
It's sharp.
What I love about this

27:12.464 --> 27:15.342
is the balance for this blade.

27:15.342 --> 27:17.302
Feels good in the hand.
It will cut.

27:17.302 --> 27:18.887
‐ Thank you so much.

27:18.887 --> 27:20.639
‐ All right, Benton, your turn.
You ready?

27:20.639 --> 27:22.057
Let's do it.
‐ Let's do this.

27:22.057 --> 27:29.064
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:34.152 --> 27:36.071
‐ Thank you, Jesus.

27:36.071 --> 27:38.657
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:38.657 --> 27:40.158
‐ All right, Benton, let's talk
about your blade here.

27:40.158 --> 27:42.661
First up, your edge.

27:42.661 --> 27:44.663
Don't let that hairy mess
fool you right there.

27:44.663 --> 27:48.375
What happened, actually,
here is, this much it did cut.

27:48.375 --> 27:51.795
The rest of that
was just pulled.

27:51.795 --> 27:53.755
I like the flare
you have there.

27:53.755 --> 27:55.841
I can retain it.
I can tell where the edge is.

27:55.841 --> 27:58.051
And more importantly...

27:58.051 --> 27:59.344
it will cut.

27:59.344 --> 28:00.554
‐ Thank you.

28:00.554 --> 28:02.180
‐ All right, Josh,
your turn.

28:02.180 --> 28:03.223
‐ Go ahead.

28:03.223 --> 28:04.266
‐ Let's do this.

28:04.266 --> 28:11.273
♪ ♪

28:17.487 --> 28:20.532
‐ All right, Josh, let's talk
about your blade here.

28:20.532 --> 28:21.575
First up, the edge.

28:21.575 --> 28:23.118
As you can see,

28:23.118 --> 28:26.079
it did cut parts
of the horsehair right there.

28:26.079 --> 28:28.707
It didn't pull anything else.
It just stopped as it cut.

28:28.707 --> 28:30.876
Now, your handle construction.

28:30.876 --> 28:32.502
Thank God for the finger weld
right there

28:32.502 --> 28:34.087
because once I put
that on there,

28:34.087 --> 28:35.923
it allowed me to be able
to get a good grip

28:35.923 --> 28:37.466
because you don't much
of flare there

28:37.466 --> 28:39.176
for anything that's
going out that way.

28:39.176 --> 28:40.886
But it will cut.

28:40.886 --> 28:42.930
‐ Thank you.

28:42.930 --> 28:44.556
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
it's time for one of you

28:44.556 --> 28:45.891
to leave The Forge.

28:45.891 --> 28:48.060
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

28:48.060 --> 28:51.229
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:51.229 --> 28:53.315
Josh, your blade
didn't make the cut.

28:53.315 --> 28:55.108
David Baker's gonna
tell you why.

28:55.108 --> 28:56.735
‐ Josh, in both of our tests,

28:56.735 --> 28:58.320
your handle was an issue,

28:58.320 --> 29:00.155
and that obtuse edge
you have on your blade

29:00.155 --> 29:02.908
just didn't cut hair
as well as the others.

29:02.908 --> 29:04.576
‐ Josh, please surrender
your blade.

29:04.576 --> 29:07.079
<i>‐ This experience</i>
<i>has just been</i>

29:07.079 --> 29:08.747
<i>the coolest thing</i>
<i>I've ever done.</i>

29:08.747 --> 29:10.415
<i>I definitely learned some</i>
<i>knowledge that</i>

29:10.415 --> 29:12.584
<i>I'm gonna put forward</i>
<i>to my future blades,</i>

29:12.584 --> 29:14.169
so that's a win in my book.

29:14.169 --> 29:15.754
<i>This is totally worth it.</i>

29:15.754 --> 29:17.005
I had a blast.

29:17.005 --> 29:20.133
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:20.133 --> 29:21.760
‐ Bladesmiths,
congratulations.

29:21.760 --> 29:23.637
You've made it to the final
round of this competition.

29:23.637 --> 29:25.764
Now it's time for you to go
back to your home forges

29:25.764 --> 29:28.433
and re‐create this iconic
weapon from history...

29:28.433 --> 29:30.936
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:30.936 --> 29:31.979
A bhuj.

29:31.979 --> 29:33.647
[both laugh]

29:33.647 --> 29:35.774
<i>Named after</i>
<i>the Indian city of Bhuj,</i>

29:35.774 --> 29:38.318
<i>this 18th century hybrid</i>
<i>axe knife was often used</i>

29:38.318 --> 29:41.279
<i>by the armies and bodyguards</i>
<i>of monarchs known as Raja.</i>

29:41.279 --> 29:43.782
<i>Featuring a broad single‐edge</i>
<i>blade mounted to a long haft,</i>

29:43.782 --> 29:45.617
<i>the lethal weapon</i>
<i>could be wielded</i>

29:45.617 --> 29:47.285
<i>as powerful</i>
<i>two‐handed battle axe,</i>

29:47.285 --> 29:49.830
<i>ideal for both hacking</i>
<i>and slashing.</i>

29:49.830 --> 29:52.290
<i>Warriors could also impose</i>
<i>stealthy and deadly attacks</i>

29:52.290 --> 29:53.917
<i>with a small stiletto dagger</i>

29:53.917 --> 29:56.003
<i>concealed within the haft</i>
<i>and pommel.</i>

29:56.003 --> 29:58.130
<i>This brutal</i>
<i>yet highly ornate weapon</i>

29:58.130 --> 30:00.007
<i>was often inlaid</i>
<i>with gold and silver</i>

30:00.007 --> 30:01.591
<i>and features</i>
<i>an elephant's head,</i>

30:01.591 --> 30:03.468
<i>a sacred animal.</i>

30:03.468 --> 30:05.846
<i>Video game enthusiasts</i>
<i>can virtually wield the bhuj</i>

30:05.846 --> 30:09.307
<i>as a Rajput warrior in</i>
<i>the game "Deadliest Warrior."</i>

30:09.307 --> 30:11.810
Gentlemen, make sure
that your blades

30:11.810 --> 30:13.437
fall within
the following parameters:

30:13.437 --> 30:15.230
the overall length
of this weapon

30:15.230 --> 30:17.816
must not exceed 36 inches.

30:17.816 --> 30:19.818
The width of your blade
as measured at the base

30:19.818 --> 30:21.820
must be at least
3 inches wide

30:21.820 --> 30:25.157
and flare to at least 3 1/2
inches with a clipped point.

30:25.157 --> 30:28.660
Additionally,
the pommel should include

30:28.660 --> 30:30.495
a 9‐ to 10‐inch stiletto

30:30.495 --> 30:32.998
that screws securely
into the handle.

30:32.998 --> 30:34.833
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:34.833 --> 30:36.710
‐ Okay, I have to make
two things.

30:36.710 --> 30:38.754
I gotta make something slice‐y
and something stab‐y.

30:38.754 --> 30:40.505
<i>I really want to win.</i>

30:40.505 --> 30:42.466
<i>It'll mean that</i>
<i>I can overcome a challenge</i>

30:42.466 --> 30:44.384
<i>and prove to the judges</i>

30:44.384 --> 30:46.136
<i>I'm a pretty</i>
<i>awesome blacksmith.</i>

30:46.136 --> 30:49.014
‐ Gentlemen, you'll have
four days at your home forges

30:49.014 --> 30:51.725
in which to complete
all this work.

30:51.725 --> 30:53.602
At the end of those four days,
you'll return to present

30:53.602 --> 30:55.562
your weapons to our panel
of expert judges,

30:55.562 --> 30:57.731
and after they've
thoroughly tested them,

30:57.731 --> 31:00.484
they'll declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

31:00.484 --> 31:02.486
who also receives $10,000.

31:02.486 --> 31:05.238
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in four days.

31:05.238 --> 31:06.865
‐ Good luck.
‐ Good luck to you, buddy.

31:06.865 --> 31:08.283
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:08.283 --> 31:09.743
‐ So it's day one.

31:09.743 --> 31:11.411
I'm back home
in Evansville, Indiana,

31:11.411 --> 31:13.205
and I'm ready to get started
on this bhuj build.

31:13.205 --> 31:16.500
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:16.500 --> 31:18.376
I'm working
on the dagger first.

31:18.376 --> 31:20.879
I think it's the easiest thing
to warm up and start with.

31:20.879 --> 31:22.881
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:22.881 --> 31:24.716
I really gotta watch
my dimensions.

31:24.716 --> 31:25.884
<i>This dagger,</i>
<i>as I'm forging it,</i>

31:25.884 --> 31:27.469
<i>I'm keeping in mind that</i>

31:27.469 --> 31:28.929
where the ricasso
and the transition

31:28.929 --> 31:30.388
from the blade to the tang is,

31:30.388 --> 31:33.350
<i>I gotta make sure</i>
<i>I'm not too wide</i>

31:33.350 --> 31:35.227
<i>to go inside the handle</i>
<i>and the pipe.</i>

31:35.227 --> 31:36.770
I gotta make sure
I'm not too narrow,

31:36.770 --> 31:38.480
<i>or this thing's gonna</i>
<i>rattle around,</i>

31:38.480 --> 31:40.899
so I really have a tight
window that I need to fit in.

31:40.899 --> 31:43.110
Good enough for now.

31:43.110 --> 31:45.904
<i>I made some great progress,</i>
<i>but I've got a lot to do.</i>

31:45.904 --> 31:46.905
It's freaking me out.

31:46.905 --> 31:49.658
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:49.658 --> 31:51.910
‐ It's day one.
I'm here at the home forge.

31:51.910 --> 31:53.078
‐ Getting it warm in here, man.
It's freezing.

31:53.078 --> 31:54.746
<i>I'm making a bhuj.</i>

31:54.746 --> 31:57.582
It's a little bit bougie,
I would say,

31:57.582 --> 31:59.292
a little bourgeois.

31:59.292 --> 32:01.753
<i>It's not only</i>
<i>a piece for warfare,</i>

32:01.753 --> 32:03.922
but it's a really
artistic expression

32:03.922 --> 32:06.133
<i>of whoever's carrying it.</i>

32:06.133 --> 32:08.135
I'm thinking of doing
some San Mai,

32:08.135 --> 32:10.387
so sandwiching it
with mild steel.

32:10.387 --> 32:13.932
That'll just make it
that much more tough.

32:13.932 --> 32:16.309
I chose San Mai
to really bring the most

32:16.309 --> 32:17.936
out of these two different
types of steels.

32:17.936 --> 32:19.604
<i>The mild steel is very tough</i>

32:19.604 --> 32:21.940
and can take a lot of bending
without cracking,

32:21.940 --> 32:24.651
while a hardened 5160
in the center

32:24.651 --> 32:28.029
is just coming down where
I need it along the edge.

32:28.029 --> 32:31.658
So to get the billet
down to a more manageable size,

32:31.658 --> 32:35.245
I hot‐cut off the excess,
and as I'm hot‐cutting,

32:35.245 --> 32:37.205
<i>I'm putting a lot</i>
<i>of stresses on those welds,</i>

32:37.205 --> 32:39.332
<i>and one of the pieces</i>
<i>of mild steel</i>

32:39.332 --> 32:40.625
is wanting to kind of rip away.

32:43.795 --> 32:45.297
‐ That's pretty bad news.

32:45.297 --> 32:48.008
From hot‐cutting it,
all the stresses on it

32:48.008 --> 32:50.051
found a weak point right there.

32:50.051 --> 32:52.262
<i>So in order to fix</i>
<i>that delamination,</i>

32:52.262 --> 32:53.930
<i>I got a few more</i>
<i>tries of forge welding</i>

32:53.930 --> 32:56.141
<i>it up with the thickness</i>
<i>that I have.</i>

32:56.141 --> 32:58.894
If I get too thin,
then it's a lost cause.

32:58.894 --> 33:01.062
<i>I just hope</i>
<i>I can make this work.</i>

33:01.062 --> 33:02.189
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:02.189 --> 33:03.732
<i>‐ Not only is it day two,</i>

33:03.732 --> 33:06.902
but it is also
my 28th birthday.

33:06.902 --> 33:08.904
<i>Creating a challenge weapon</i>
<i>in my home shop,</i>

33:08.904 --> 33:11.031
that's a pretty cool
birthday present.

33:11.031 --> 33:14.326
<i>Today I'm gonna start forging</i>
<i>the larger blade of the bhuj.</i>

33:14.326 --> 33:17.913
So what I'm trying to do
is split this tang off of here.

33:17.913 --> 33:21.291
I've gotta form my clip point.

33:21.291 --> 33:23.335
<i>Then I can draw my length out</i>

33:23.335 --> 33:24.961
and that shape will follow

33:24.961 --> 33:26.963
<i>and then I can start</i>
<i>getting that swoop</i>

33:26.963 --> 33:30.050
<i>that I need</i>
<i>for that bhuj look.</i>

33:30.050 --> 33:32.177
Time to get
this bad boy quenched.

33:32.177 --> 33:35.096
<i>This is the moment</i>
<i>that I really need to nail,</i>

33:35.096 --> 33:38.183
<i>and I am praying that this</i>
<i>thing's gonna stay straight.</i>

33:38.183 --> 33:40.602
I pull it out...

33:40.602 --> 33:43.980
[laughing]

33:43.980 --> 33:46.107
That thing's harder than
$9 worth of Jawbreakers

33:46.107 --> 33:47.651
and straight as an arrow, man.

33:47.651 --> 33:49.402
Pretty good birthday.

33:49.402 --> 33:52.989
<i>‐ It's day two</i>
<i>and I'm looking at the blade</i>

33:52.989 --> 33:56.576
and I'm not 100%
on the laminations

33:56.576 --> 33:58.828
<i>on the San Mai.</i>

33:58.828 --> 34:01.206
So it's seeming to make
the best sense

34:01.206 --> 34:02.624
just to scrap it
and start over.

34:02.624 --> 34:04.459
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:04.459 --> 34:06.419
<i>I'm gonna use a big old piece</i>
<i>of leaf spring</i>

34:06.419 --> 34:09.089
and see what I can do
a second time around.

34:09.089 --> 34:12.467
Starting over with the 5160
mono‐steel blade,

34:12.467 --> 34:14.094
<i>time is really at a premium.</i>

34:14.094 --> 34:15.303
<i>I may not finish.</i>

34:15.303 --> 34:18.431
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:18.431 --> 34:21.309
‐ So it's the start
of day three.

34:21.309 --> 34:23.520
<i>I have to start putting a lot</i>
<i>of puzzle pieces together</i>

34:23.520 --> 34:25.397
<i>and do a lot of fabrication.</i>

34:25.397 --> 34:27.691
60 is too hard.

34:27.691 --> 34:30.193
I think I need to temper
this some more.

34:30.193 --> 34:32.821
A little hard for my liking
for what it's gonna be doing,

34:32.821 --> 34:35.615
so I'll soften it some more.

34:35.615 --> 34:37.951
Trying to make sure that my
blade gets up to temperature

34:37.951 --> 34:40.245
and relieves stress,
so that way I've got a nice,

34:40.245 --> 34:43.999
flexible yet strong blade.

34:43.999 --> 34:46.793
<i>If I don't get these blades</i>
<i>softened and more flexible,</i>

34:46.793 --> 34:48.253
they're more likely to snap.

34:48.253 --> 34:49.879
Right now,
they're very brittle.

34:49.879 --> 34:52.215
If I heat up the very end

34:52.215 --> 34:55.176
and keep heating up the end,
the heat will travel

34:55.176 --> 34:57.387
and draw the temper
all the way down.

34:57.387 --> 34:59.973
<i>This is the best</i>
<i>I can do right now.</i>

34:59.973 --> 35:02.892
I've got my dagger tempered
so I can put my handle on.

35:02.892 --> 35:05.186
Then I'll slide my socket on,

35:05.186 --> 35:07.564
<i>weld that beast up,</i>
<i>and we're ready to go.</i>

35:07.564 --> 35:09.566
It fits right in there.

35:09.566 --> 35:11.234
My blade
is completely assembled.

35:11.234 --> 35:13.820
It's not pretty,
but it would perform.

35:13.820 --> 35:15.614
I think it's ready
to roll, man.

35:15.614 --> 35:17.657
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:17.657 --> 35:20.201
<i>‐ So yesterday, I forged</i>
<i>out the blade of my bhuj,</i>

35:20.201 --> 35:22.078
I forged out the stiletto

35:22.078 --> 35:26.458
<i>and got around to</i>
<i>heat‐treating the bhuj blade.</i>

35:26.458 --> 35:29.836
<i>Today I have to heat‐treat</i>
<i>the stiletto.</i>

35:29.836 --> 35:32.505
<i>Heat‐treating a stiletto</i>
<i>is gonna be a little tricky,</i>

35:32.505 --> 35:34.633
'cause there's zero room
for warpage

35:34.633 --> 35:35.925
'cause this thing
needs to be dead straight

35:35.925 --> 35:37.719
to be able to fit
in that handle.

35:37.719 --> 35:39.554
<i>If it's not, I mean,</i>
<i>it could hang up in there.</i>

35:39.554 --> 35:42.223
It might not even come out,
or just rub against

35:42.223 --> 35:46.811
the interior wall
and dull the blade.

35:46.811 --> 35:49.898
So it's the moment of truth.

35:49.898 --> 35:51.483
Yeah, it looks great.

35:51.483 --> 35:53.860
Looks perfectly straight.

35:53.860 --> 35:56.279
It's time to start chiseling
at the elephant head

35:56.279 --> 35:58.698
into the bolster now.

35:58.698 --> 36:00.450
I'm choosing to put
an elephant on my bhuj

36:00.450 --> 36:02.702
because that was
the traditional creature

36:02.702 --> 36:06.247
<i>they would add onto it,</i>
<i>and I'd really like to honor</i>

36:06.247 --> 36:10.418
the culture and these amazing
smiths who were creating this.

36:10.418 --> 36:12.003
There we go.

36:12.003 --> 36:13.463
So the weapon as a whole,
I think,

36:13.463 --> 36:17.050
is becoming a beautiful piece.

36:17.050 --> 36:24.015
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:28.353 --> 36:30.313
‐ Joe, Benton,
welcome back to The Forge.

36:30.313 --> 36:32.774
You fellas have had
four days at your home forges

36:32.774 --> 36:35.652
to work on your bhuj
with hidden stiletto blade.

36:35.652 --> 36:37.529
Joe, how did it go?

36:37.529 --> 36:39.406
‐ It went well.

36:39.406 --> 36:41.991
My blade's made
out of leaf spring.

36:41.991 --> 36:44.494
Got a coil spring stiletto

36:44.494 --> 36:46.454
and some etched
design work on there.

36:46.454 --> 36:47.872
‐ What about you, Benton?

36:47.872 --> 36:50.583
‐ I feel like
my build went well.

36:50.583 --> 36:55.505
My blade's out of 5160,
and my stiletto is 1084.

36:55.505 --> 36:57.841
It was a tough build,
but I feel great about it.

36:57.841 --> 36:59.968
‐ Well, gentlemen,
only one of you can be

36:59.968 --> 37:02.220
the "Forged in Fire" champion,
and to determine which one

37:02.220 --> 37:04.848
of you it will be,
it's time to test them.

37:04.848 --> 37:06.266
There will be a strength test,
a sharpness test,

37:06.266 --> 37:08.059
and up first,
the KEAL test.

37:08.059 --> 37:09.060
Doug?

37:09.060 --> 37:12.147
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:12.147 --> 37:15.024
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to the KEAL test.

37:15.024 --> 37:18.153
Your bhujes look beautiful,
but are they deadly?

37:18.153 --> 37:20.196
Well, to find that out,
I will take your weapon

37:20.196 --> 37:23.616
and deliver killing blows
on two pig carcasses.

37:23.616 --> 37:25.160
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:25.160 --> 37:27.036
Joe, you're up first. Ready?
‐ I'm ready.

37:27.036 --> 37:29.038
‐ Let's do this.

37:29.038 --> 37:32.375
<i>‐ My heart's racing,</i>
<i>my knees are rattling,</i>

37:32.375 --> 37:34.169
<i>and my blade has to go</i>
<i>through hide.</i>

37:34.169 --> 37:36.671
<i>It has to go</i>
<i>through meat, bone,</i>

37:36.671 --> 37:39.090
and not only one pig
but two of them.

37:39.090 --> 37:41.342
<i>I just feel like anything</i>
<i>can happen, you know?</i>

37:41.342 --> 37:43.386
<i>Rushing on a blade like this,</i>

37:43.386 --> 37:45.305
<i>there's a lot</i>
<i>of imperfections.</i>

37:45.305 --> 37:47.348
Worst‐case scenario,
it just breaks in half.

37:51.060 --> 37:58.026
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:04.991 --> 38:06.659
‐ Nice.

38:06.659 --> 38:13.666
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:23.301 --> 38:25.011
‐ Oh, man.

38:25.011 --> 38:26.346
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:26.346 --> 38:27.764
[exhales]

38:27.764 --> 38:31.142
‐ First up,
this blade is sharp.

38:31.142 --> 38:34.312
The point is easy enough
to get into the carcass

38:34.312 --> 38:37.732
and slash on the way out.
It's got a great feel to it.

38:37.732 --> 38:39.609
Nice stiletto.

38:39.609 --> 38:42.821
There's even a handle that
you put on there so it

38:42.821 --> 38:45.114
gets a nice look to it.

38:45.114 --> 38:48.952
Overall, sir, this bhuj...

38:48.952 --> 38:50.036
will KEAL.

38:50.036 --> 38:51.663
‐ Thanks, Doug.

38:51.663 --> 38:52.872
‐ All right, Benton.

38:52.872 --> 38:54.415
Are you ready to ham it up?

38:54.415 --> 38:55.416
‐ Ready to rock 'n' roll.

38:55.416 --> 38:57.961
‐ Let's do this.

38:57.961 --> 39:00.964
<i>‐ Joe's bhuj performed</i>
<i>incredibly.</i>

39:00.964 --> 39:03.383
<i>It split that pig in half.</i>

39:03.383 --> 39:06.678
<i>And now it's my turn,</i>
<i>and I'm terrified.</i>

39:06.678 --> 39:09.180
<i>I've never made this style</i>
<i>of weapon before.</i>

39:09.180 --> 39:11.558
<i>I've never been able to test</i>
<i>this kind of construction.</i>

39:11.558 --> 39:13.393
I just don't know
how it's gonna hold up.

39:13.393 --> 39:20.400
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:23.862 --> 39:27.031
Oh, [bleep].

39:27.031 --> 39:28.366
‐ I'm sorry, man.

39:28.366 --> 39:31.703
‐ That's a big piece
of shrapnel.

39:31.703 --> 39:32.829
‐ [bleep] damn it.

39:32.829 --> 39:35.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:35.748 --> 39:37.083
‐ Well, Benton,

39:37.083 --> 39:38.209
one of the things
I like about this,

39:38.209 --> 39:39.752
you put on the leather.

39:39.752 --> 39:42.213
It gave you a very nice
area to hold onto,

39:42.213 --> 39:44.591
and it's ovoid.
I can tell where the edge is.

39:44.591 --> 39:47.844
But the obvious happened.

39:47.844 --> 39:49.679
It's a coarse grain
structure here.

39:49.679 --> 39:51.347
‐ I should have
normalized that tang

39:51.347 --> 39:54.475
much better than I did,
but when you're grinding

39:54.475 --> 39:56.895
<i>away long days in the shop</i>
<i>during this challenge</i>

39:56.895 --> 39:58.688
<i>and you're just focused</i>
<i>on the finish line,</i>

39:58.688 --> 40:00.356
<i>it's easy to overlook</i>
<i>some things,</i>

40:00.356 --> 40:02.233
and, obviously, I did.

40:02.233 --> 40:05.361
‐ Well, Benton, any warrior
knows that if you leave

40:05.361 --> 40:08.239
a piece of shrapnel that
big in a target, it's deadly.

40:08.239 --> 40:11.534
However, a warrior also knows
that his weapon needs to be

40:11.534 --> 40:14.746
strong, and your blade has
suffered a catastrophic failure

40:14.746 --> 40:16.664
in our very first test,

40:16.664 --> 40:20.418
and, therefore, you cannot move
forward in this competition.

40:20.418 --> 40:22.211
Come on, brother.

40:22.211 --> 40:24.213
Did a great job, man.

40:24.213 --> 40:26.424
<i>‐ I feel pretty bummed,</i>
<i>but this challenge has been</i>

40:26.424 --> 40:29.385
<i>both very difficult and</i>
<i>invigorating at the same time.</i>

40:29.385 --> 40:32.305
I've made things that I've
never made before,

40:32.305 --> 40:33.765
and I've overcome
some challenges

40:33.765 --> 40:35.224
that I've never had
to face before,

40:35.224 --> 40:37.101
so, overall,
it was a great experience.

40:37.101 --> 40:40.939
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:40.939 --> 40:44.067
‐ Joe, your blade is sharp,
deadly, and strong,

40:44.067 --> 40:46.235
and you are the new
"Forged in Fire" champion,

40:46.235 --> 40:47.946
and that's a title
that comes with a check

40:47.946 --> 40:49.948
for $10,000.
Good job.

40:49.948 --> 40:51.324
[applause]

40:51.324 --> 40:52.283
How you feeling right now?

40:52.283 --> 40:53.785
‐ It's a little surreal.

40:53.785 --> 40:56.079
I'm a "Forged in Fire"
champion.

40:56.079 --> 40:58.790
<i>I won, but, you know,</i>
<i>it would've been nice to win</i>

40:58.790 --> 41:00.625
<i>after the three tests.</i>

41:00.625 --> 41:03.461
<i>But this has been</i>
<i>a totally unique opportunity.</i>

41:03.461 --> 41:06.214
<i>It's really a big affirmation</i>
<i>of my abilities.</i>

41:06.214 --> 41:07.256
<i>It's amazing.</i>

41:07.256 --> 41:12.303
<i>♪ ♪</i>
